            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Goldberg, at 46, is a man whose hands create tangible beauty. Born in Berkeley in the late 70s, he was the second of two children, a son to a high school history teacher mother and a civil engineer father. His childhood was characterized by a comfortable, intellectual environment. He spent hours in his father\u2019s workshop, fascinated by the transformation of raw materials into functional objects. This early exposure ignited a spark that would later define his career.\n\nThough he toyed with the idea of engineering, his artistic leanings led him to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Industrial Design at California College of the Arts in Oakland. It was a formative period, where he honed his eye for form and function, sketching endlessly in notebooks filled with furniture designs. After graduating, he worked for various design firms, gaining experience and refining his aesthetic. The pivotal moment came in his early thirties when he partnered with a skilled artisan he\u2019d met through a mutual friend. Together, they founded a custom furniture manufacturing business, marrying his design vision with hands-on craftsmanship.\n\nProfessionally, David thrives on the challenge of bringing clients\u2019 visions to life, his work adorning high-end homes and offices across the city. Personally, he is a man of quiet routine. His 3.1-mile bicycle commute from his Inner Sunset apartment to the workshop in the Dogpatch is his daily ritual, a transition between his private life and creative process. He's been in a committed relationship with Sarah, a librarian, for ten years, a bond built on shared values and a mutual appreciation for thoughtful design and quiet evenings. They have a close circle of friends, often gathering for dinners and exploring the city\u2019s diverse culinary scene.\n\nDavid's future aspirations are rooted in expanding the reach of his business while maintaining the integrity of their craftsmanship. He dreams of designing and building a home from the ground up, a culmination of his design principles and practical skills. His connection to San Francisco runs deep; the city\u2019s blend of innovation, history, and natural beauty fuel his creative spirit. He finds solace in the misty mornings of the Inner Sunset and inspiration in the industrial grit of the Dogpatch. David Goldberg is not just a furniture designer; he is a craftsman, an entrepreneur, and a man whose life is as carefully constructed and aesthetically pleasing as the pieces he creates."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1. He remembered the scent of sawdust and cut metal in his father's workshop, the feel of cool steel in his small hands. It wasn't just a hobby; it was the nascent pulse of creation within him, a quiet understanding that beauty could emerge from raw materials. This was where his lifelong passion for making began, a seed planted in childhood.\n\n2. The moment he saw his thesis project, a minimalist yet functional chair, exhibited at CCA, a wave of validation washed over him. Years of sketching and failed prototypes coalesced into something tangible and admired. It solidified his belief in his design voice and the path he needed to follow.\n\n3. That first handshake with Mark, his business partner, felt unexpectedly significant. There was a shared vision, a mutual respect for dedication to craft. It wasn't just forming a business; it was finding the missing piece, the hands to translate his designs into reality, a turning point in his career.\n\n4. Hearing Sarah laugh, truly laugh, for the first time felt like sunshine breaking through the fog. There was an ease, a genuine connection that went beyond words.  It was the quiet beginning of a deep, enduring relationship built on mutual understanding and shared comfort.\n\n5. Riding his bike home through the Inner Sunset fog after a long day, the damp air on his face felt like a cleansing ritual.  The city\u2019s rhythm, its blend of hard edges and soft beauty, resonated with him, a constant source of grounding and inspiration for his craft and life."
